{
    "publish_date": "2012-01-09T20:17:32.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT6M14S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "Say you&#39;re me and\nyou&#39;re in math class,", 
            "dur": "1.72", 
            "start": "0"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and you&#39;re doodling\nflowery petally things.", 
            "dur": "1.86", 
            "start": "1.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you want something with\nlots of overlapping petals,", 
            "dur": "2.26", 
            "start": "3.58"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;re probably following\na loose sort of rule", 
            "dur": "1.916", 
            "start": "5.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that goes something like this.", 
            "dur": "1.354", 
            "start": "7.756"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Add new petals where there&#39;s\ngaps between old petals.", 
            "dur": "3.42", 
            "start": "9.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can try doing\nthis precisely.", 
            "dur": "1.64", 
            "start": "12.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Start with some number\nof petals, say five,", 
            "dur": "2.64", 
            "start": "14.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "then add another\nlayer in between.", 
            "dur": "2.02", 
            "start": "16.81"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But the next layer, you have to\nadd 10, then the next has 20.", 
            "dur": "2.642", 
            "start": "18.83"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The inconvenient part\nof this is that you", 
            "dur": "1.708", 
            "start": "21.472"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "have to finish a layer\nbefore everything is even.", 
            "dur": "2.51", 
            "start": "23.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Ideally, you&#39;d have\na rule that just", 
            "dur": "1.5", 
            "start": "25.69"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "lets you add petals\nuntil you get bored.", 
            "dur": "2.64", 
            "start": "27.19"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now imagine you&#39;re\na plant, and you", 
            "dur": "1.51", 
            "start": "29.83"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "want to grow in a\nway that spreads out", 
            "dur": "1.583", 
            "start": "31.34"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "your leaves to catch the\nmost possible sunlight.", 
            "dur": "2.807", 
            "start": "32.923"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Unfortunately,\nand I hope I&#39;m not", 
            "dur": "1.69", 
            "start": "35.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "presuming too much in\nthinking that, as a plant,", 
            "dur": "2.44", 
            "start": "37.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;re not very smart.", 
            "dur": "1.714", 
            "start": "39.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You don&#39;t know how to add\nnumber to create a series,", 
            "dur": "2.166", 
            "start": "41.574"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you don&#39;t know geometry\nand proportions,", 
            "dur": "1.666", 
            "start": "43.74"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and can&#39;t draw spirals, or\nrectangles, or slug cats.", 
            "dur": "3.374", 
            "start": "45.406"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But maybe you could\nfollow one simple rule.", 
            "dur": "2.854", 
            "start": "48.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Botanists have\nnoticed that plants", 
            "dur": "1.416", 
            "start": "51.634"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "seem to be fairly\nconsistent when", 
            "dur": "1.62", 
            "start": "53.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it comes to the angle between\none leaf and the next.", 
            "dur": "2.762", 
            "start": "54.67"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So let&#39;s see what you\ncould do with that.", 
            "dur": "1.708", 
            "start": "57.432"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you grow your first leaf,\nand if you didn&#39;t change angle", 
            "dur": "2.25", 
            "start": "59.14"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "at all, then the\nnext leaf you grow", 
            "dur": "1.56", 
            "start": "61.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "would be directly above it.", 
            "dur": "1.259", 
            "start": "62.95"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So that&#39;s no good,\nbecause it blocks", 
            "dur": "1.14", 
            "start": "64.209"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "all the light or something.", 
            "dur": "1.281", 
            "start": "65.349"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can go 180 degrees, to\nhave the next leaf directly", 
            "dur": "2.76", 
            "start": "66.63"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "opposite, which seems ideal.", 
            "dur": "1.46", 
            "start": "69.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Only once you go 180\nagain, the third leaf", 
            "dur": "1.97", 
            "start": "70.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is right over the first.", 
            "dur": "1.53", 
            "start": "72.82"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, any\nfraction of a circle", 
            "dur": "1.667", 
            "start": "74.35"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with a whole number\nas a base is going", 
            "dur": "1.583", 
            "start": "76.017"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to have complete overlap\nafter that number of turns.", 
            "dur": "2.94", 
            "start": "77.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And unlike when you&#39;re\ndoodling, as a plant", 
            "dur": "1.989", 
            "start": "80.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;re not smart enough to see\nyou&#39;ve gone all the way around", 
            "dur": "2.541", 
            "start": "82.529"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and now should switch to\nadding things in between.", 
            "dur": "2.47", 
            "start": "85.07"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you try and\npostpone the overlap", 
            "dur": "1.73", 
            "start": "87.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by making the\nfraction really small,", 
            "dur": "1.902", 
            "start": "89.27"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you just get a ton of\noverlap in the beginning,", 
            "dur": "1.958", 
            "start": "91.172"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and waste all this space,\nwhich is completely disastrous.", 
            "dur": "3.15", 
            "start": "93.13"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or maybe other\nfractions are good.", 
            "dur": "1.57", 
            "start": "96.28"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The kind that position leaves\nin a star like pattern.", 
            "dur": "2.41", 
            "start": "97.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It will be a while\nbefore it overlaps,", 
            "dur": "1.69", 
            "start": "100.26"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and the leaves will be more\nevenly spaced in the meantime.", 
            "dur": "3.14", 
            "start": "101.95"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But what if there\nwere a fraction that", 
            "dur": "1.63", 
            "start": "105.09"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "never completely overlapped?", 
            "dur": "2", 
            "start": "106.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "For any rational fraction,\neventually the star will close.", 
            "dur": "3.14", 
            "start": "108.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But what if you used\nan irrational number?", 
            "dur": "1.89", 
            "start": "111.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The kind of number that can&#39;t\nbe expressed as a whole number", 
            "dur": "2.499", 
            "start": "113.75"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "ratio.", 
            "dur": "0.591", 
            "start": "116.249"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "What if you used the\nmost irrational number?", 
            "dur": "2.78", 
            "start": "116.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you think it sounds weird\nto say one irrational number is", 
            "dur": "2.5", 
            "start": "119.62"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "more irrational than\nanother, well, you", 
            "dur": "1.59", 
            "start": "122.12"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "might want to become\na number theorist.", 
            "dur": "1.55", 
            "start": "123.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you are a number\ntheorist, you", 
            "dur": "1.4", 
            "start": "125.26"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "might tell us that phi is\nthe most irrational number.", 
            "dur": "2.86", 
            "start": "126.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or you might say, that&#39;s like\nsaying, of all the integers,", 
            "dur": "2.64", 
            "start": "129.52"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "1 is the integer-iest.", 
            "dur": "1.435", 
            "start": "132.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or you might\ndisagree completely.", 
            "dur": "1.375", 
            "start": "133.595"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But anyway, phi.", 
            "dur": "1.29", 
            "start": "134.97"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s more than 1, but less\nthan 2, more than 3/2,", 
            "dur": "3.33", 
            "start": "136.26"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "less than 5/3.", 
            "dur": "1.35", 
            "start": "139.59"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Greater than 8/5,\nbut 13/8 is too big.", 
            "dur": "3.62", 
            "start": "140.94"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "21/13 is just a\nlittle too small,", 
            "dur": "2.17", 
            "start": "144.56"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and 34/21 is even closer,\nbut too big, and so on.", 
            "dur": "3.99", 
            "start": "146.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Each pair of adjacent\nFibonacci numbers", 
            "dur": "2.32", 
            "start": "150.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "creates a ratio that\ngets closer and closer", 
            "dur": "2.65", 
            "start": "153.04"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to Phi as the numbers increase.", 
            "dur": "2.02", 
            "start": "155.69"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Those are the same numbers on\nthe sides of these squares.", 
            "dur": "3.076", 
            "start": "157.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now stop being a\nnumber theorist,", 
            "dur": "1.374", 
            "start": "160.786"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and start being a plant again.", 
            "dur": "1.85", 
            "start": "162.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You put your first leaf\nsomewhere, and the second leaf", 
            "dur": "2.3", 
            "start": "164.01"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "at an angle, which is\none Phi-th of a circle.", 
            "dur": "2.786", 
            "start": "166.31"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which depending\non whether you&#39;re", 
            "dur": "1.374", 
            "start": "169.096"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "going one way or the other,\ncould be about 222.5 degrees,", 
            "dur": "3.78", 
            "start": "170.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or about 137.5.", 
            "dur": "2.21", 
            "start": "174.25"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Great, your second leaf is\npretty far from the first,", 
            "dur": "2.71", 
            "start": "176.46"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "gets lots of space in the sun.", 
            "dur": "1.42", 
            "start": "179.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And now let&#39;s add the next one\na Phi-th of the circle away.", 
            "dur": "2.85", 
            "start": "180.59"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And again, and again.", 
            "dur": "2.55", 
            "start": "183.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can see how new\nleaves tend to pop up", 
            "dur": "1.73", 
            "start": "185.99"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in the spaces left\nbetween old leaves,", 
            "dur": "2.08", 
            "start": "187.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but it never quite\nfills things evenly.", 
            "dur": "1.95", 
            "start": "189.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So there&#39;s always room\nfor one more leaf,", 
            "dur": "2.04", 
            "start": "191.75"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "without having to do\na whole new layer.", 
            "dur": "2", 
            "start": "193.79"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s very practical and as a\nplant you probably like this.", 
            "dur": "2.98", 
            "start": "195.79"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It would also be a good\nway to give lots of room", 
            "dur": "2", 
            "start": "198.77"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to seed pods and\npetals and stuff.", 
            "dur": "1.98", 
            "start": "200.77"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "As a plant that\nfollows this scheme,", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "202.75"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;d be at an advantage.", 
            "dur": "1.78", 
            "start": "204.87"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Where do spirals come in?", 
            "dur": "1.51", 
            "start": "206.65"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s doodle a pinecone\nusing this same method.", 
            "dur": "2.02", 
            "start": "208.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "By the way, you can make\nyour own phi angle-a-tron", 
            "dur": "2.27", 
            "start": "210.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by dog-earing a corner\nof your notebook.", 
            "dur": "2.35", 
            "start": "212.45"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you folded it so\nthe edges of the line--", 
            "dur": "1.95", 
            "start": "214.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You have 45 degrees\nplus 90, which is 135.", 
            "dur": "3.89", 
            "start": "216.75"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Pretty close to 137.5.", 
            "dur": "2.365", 
            "start": "220.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you&#39;re careful, you can\nslip in a couple more degrees.", 
            "dur": "2.375", 
            "start": "223.005"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Detach your angle-a-tron\nand you&#39;re good to go.", 
            "dur": "2.64", 
            "start": "225.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Add each new pine cone-y\nthing a phi angle around,", 
            "dur": "2.71", 
            "start": "228.02"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and make them a little\nfarther out each time.", 
            "dur": "2.317", 
            "start": "230.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which you can keep\ntrack of by marking", 
            "dur": "1.583", 
            "start": "233.047"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the distance on\nyour angle-a-tron.", 
            "dur": "1.74", 
            "start": "234.63"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Check it out!", 
            "dur": "0.62", 
            "start": "236.37"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The spirals form by themselves.", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "236.99"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And if we count the number of\narms, look it&#39;s five and eight.", 
            "dur": "3.43", 
            "start": "239.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you&#39;re wondering\nwhy spirals would form,", 
            "dur": "1.88", 
            "start": "242.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and why always with\nFibonacci numbers,", 
            "dur": "2.554", 
            "start": "244.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you could morph back into a\nnumber theorist, or a geometer", 
            "dur": "2.416", 
            "start": "246.974"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or something.", 
            "dur": "0.5", 
            "start": "249.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But here&#39;s just a\nlittle bit of intuition.", 
            "dur": "1.75", 
            "start": "249.89"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "One simple way to do\na flower is to start", 
            "dur": "1.69", 
            "start": "251.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with a certain number\nof petals, say five.", 
            "dur": "1.76", 
            "start": "253.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And when you go back\naround, add the next layer", 
            "dur": "1.958", 
            "start": "255.09"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "close to the first, but bigger.", 
            "dur": "1.332", 
            "start": "257.048"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Each layer adds five new petals\nand the five arms spiral out.", 
            "dur": "3.622", 
            "start": "258.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Looks pretty spiral-ey to me.", 
            "dur": "1.208", 
            "start": "262.002"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now go back to phi.", 
            "dur": "1.57", 
            "start": "263.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You put out three petals\nbefore you go back around.", 
            "dur": "2.97", 
            "start": "264.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And if I make them\nreally wide, the next lap", 
            "dur": "2.15", 
            "start": "267.75"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "adds three petals that overlap\na bunch with the first,", 
            "dur": "2.58", 
            "start": "269.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and so on.", 
            "dur": "1.19", 
            "start": "272.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If I started with\nskinnier petals though,", 
            "dur": "2.13", 
            "start": "273.67"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the second time you go around it\ndoesn&#39;t quite overlap so much.", 
            "dur": "2.93", 
            "start": "275.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And it takes eight petals\nbefore it goes around twice", 
            "dur": "2.38", 
            "start": "278.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and they overlap enough\nfor you to see the spirals.", 
            "dur": "2.49", 
            "start": "281.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So this time I get 8 and 13.", 
            "dur": "2.09", 
            "start": "283.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I mean none of the spirals\nare actually physically there", 
            "dur": "2.63", 
            "start": "285.69"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "on any of these plants,\nit&#39;s just the plant bits", 
            "dur": "2.01", 
            "start": "288.32"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are close enough that\nyou can see the pattern.", 
            "dur": "2.31", 
            "start": "290.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So all the plant needs to\ndo to get awesome Fibonacci", 
            "dur": "2.32", 
            "start": "292.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "numbers of spirals, is add new\nbits at 137.5 degree angles.", 
            "dur": "5.4", 
            "start": "294.96"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The rest takes care of itself.", 
            "dur": "2.35", 
            "start": "300.36"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That the Fibonacci series\nis in so many things", 
            "dur": "2.58", 
            "start": "302.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "really says less\nabout those things,", 
            "dur": "1.94", 
            "start": "305.29"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and more about mathematics.", 
            "dur": "1.15", 
            "start": "307.23"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I mean that&#39;s what\nmathematics is all about.", 
            "dur": "1.833", 
            "start": "308.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Simple rules,\ncomplex consequences.", 
            "dur": "1.907", 
            "start": "310.213"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "A process so easy that\neven a plant can do it,", 
            "dur": "2.56", 
            "start": "312.12"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "can turn into these amazing\nstructures all around us.", 
            "dur": "3.41", 
            "start": "314.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Just like a few\nsimple postulates", 
            "dur": "1.57", 
            "start": "318.09"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "can give us an incredibly\npowerful geometry.", 
            "dur": "2.467", 
            "start": "319.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I mean that&#39;s all assuming\nthat a plant can do it.", 
            "dur": "2.083", 
            "start": "322.127"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But measuring the angles\nbetween plant bits,", 
            "dur": "1.833", 
            "start": "324.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you can see they obviously\ndo do it, somehow.", 
            "dur": "2.564", 
            "start": "326.043"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I mean, it&#39;s not like\nthey have angle-trons,", 
            "dur": "1.833", 
            "start": "328.607"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but plants have been\naround a long time,", 
            "dur": "1.666", 
            "start": "330.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and have had a lot of\npractice, so that probably", 
            "dur": "2.214", 
            "start": "332.106"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "explains everything.", 
            "dur": "1.72", 
            "start": "334.32"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And so we always get spirals of\n5 and 8 on this flower, 5 and 8", 
            "dur": "3.78", 
            "start": "336.04"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "on this artichoke, 5\nand 8 on this pine cone,", 
            "dur": "2.09", 
            "start": "339.82"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "even this cauliflower has 1,\n2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7-- um, anyway,", 
            "dur": "5.23", 
            "start": "341.91"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "we always get 1, 2\n3, 4, 5, 6, 7-- Huh.", 
            "dur": "4.23", 
            "start": "347.14"
        }, 
        {
